{"title_page": "Coast of Poets", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Casa de neruda isla negra.jpg|thumb|[[Casa de Isla Negra|Pablo Neruda's house]], [[Isla Negra]], on the [[El Quisco]] [[Communes of Chile|commune]] coast. [[Pablo Neruda]] and his wife [[Matilde Urrutia]] are buried on these grounds. The site currently includes a museum in honour of the Chilean [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel laureate]].]]\n\nThe '''Coast of Poets''' is a cultural space in the [[Valpara\u00edso Region]] of [[Chile]], named for four world-renowned Chilean poets ([[Pablo Neruda]], [[Vicente Huidobro]], [[Nicanor Parra]] and [[Violeta Parra]]).\n\n==Description==\n\n[[File:Vicente huidobro.jpg|thumb|[[Vicente Huidobro]].]]\n\n[[File:Parra01f.PNG|thumb|[[Violeta Parra]].]]\n\n[[File:Perotti.jpg|thumb|[[Jos\u00e9 Perotti]].]]\n\nThe poets were the first to take up residence in this area, followed by various artists, thus creating a close link between the land and its creativity, projecting a symbolic imaginary that put Chile on the international cultural map. Places such as [[El Quisco]], [[Isla Negra]], [[Las Cruces (Chile)|Las Cruces]], [[El Tabo]] and [[Cartagena, Chile|Cartagena]] have become a hub for cultural activity.\n\nEl Quisco itself has been a meeting place for people such as [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel laureate]] [[Pablo Neruda]], who composed his famous poem ''Oda al Caldillo de Congr\u00edo'' (English: \u201cOde to Conger Chowder\u201d) in the local restaurant Chez Camilo;<ref name=\"Beach history\">[http://www.thisischile.cl/Article.aspx?id=2674&sec=196&itz=&eje=Turismo&idioma=2&t= Beaches with history on the central coast]. This is Chile. December 11, 2009. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref> folk singer [[Violeta Parra]]; writer, poet and composer [[Clara Solovera]]; cartoonist Ren\u00e9 R\u00edos Boettiger, otherwise known as [[Pepo (cartoonist)|Pepo]], the creator of famous character [[Condorito]];<ref name=\"Beach history\" /> artist [[Jos\u00e9 Perotti]]; and painter [[Camilo Mori]], who designed the official emblem for the municipality of El Quisco.\n\nIn [[Isla Negra]], two greats of the Chilean arts, Pablo Neruda and Violeta Parra, spent long periods of time. Chilean artist [[Violeta Parra]] gave classes in crafts and folklore in Isla Negra. She worked in [[ceramic]]s, [[oil painting]] and [[Hessian (cloth)|hessian cloth]].\n\nIsla Negra was given this name by [[Pablo Neruda]], upon him sighting the black rock in the sea near his house (Isla Negra means \"Black Island\" in English). When asked what the place would be called, he said \"Isla Negra, for those rocks.\u201d\n\n:\"The sea seemed cleaner to me than the land and this is why I came to live on the coast of my homeland, amid the great foam of Isla Negra.\"<ref>[http://radioantumapu.uchile.cl/programa-134-litoral-central-de-chile-cuna-de-poetas-e-identidad-nacional/ Programa 134: Litoral central de Chile, cuna de poetas e identidad nacional]. Radio Antumapu, University of Chile. January 7, 2012. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe [[Casa de Isla Negra]] is also to be found here,<ref>[http://www.fundacionneruda.org/es/isla-negra/direccion.html Isla Negra]. Fundaci\u00f3n Neruda. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref> now Neruda's place of burial, together with his wife Matilde. On one of his many returns to Chile, in 1937, the poet sought an ideal place to write his celebrated work [[Canto General]]. Neruda bought the site of Isla Negra from a Spanish former sailor who settled in the area following the sinking of his ship in [[Punta Arenas]]. With the help of architect Germ\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez Arias, he remodeled it to resemble a ship, with low ceilings and narrow passageways. The house would become a beloved refuge for the poet. It is now administered by the Neruda Foundation, with a museum exhibiting his extensive collection of objects, including ship figureheads, shells, bottles and maps.\n\nIn [[Cartagena, Chile|Cartagena]], poet [[Vicente Huidobro]] died in January 1948. Creator and exponent of [[Creacionismo|the creationist movement]], he is considered one of the \"four greats of Chilean poetry\", alongside [[Pablo Neruda]], [[Pablo de Rokha]] and [[Gabriela Mistral]]. A house-museum dedicated to the poet was opened here in September 2013.<ref>[http://www.gob.cl/english/featured/2013/04/06/president-pinera-inaugurates-vicente-huidobro-house-museum-in-cartagena.htm President Pi\u00f1era inaugurates Vicente Huidobro house museum in Cartagena] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822171323/http://www.gob.cl/english/featured/2013/04/06/president-pinera-inaugurates-vicente-huidobro-house-museum-in-cartagena.htm |date=August 22, 2016 }}. Presidency of Chile website (www.gob.cl). April 6, 2013. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn [[Las Cruces (Chile)|Las Cruces]] lives [[Nicanor Parra]], a Chilean \"anti-poet\". Parra is credited for creating the \"anti-poetry\" movement, a literary expression that breaks with the traditional canons of poetic lyricism. One of his most recognised works is ''Poemas y Antipoemas'' (1954), where he replaces carefully written, metaphorical syntax with everyday, direct language. Considered one of the most influential Spanish poetry collections of the twentieth century, ''Poemas y Antipoemas'' is cited as an inspiration by American Beat writers like [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2011/12/01/cervantes-prize-nicanor-parra.html | work=CBC News | title=Chilean poet Nicanor Parra wins Cervantes Prize | date=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nicanor Parra Havana 1965|url=http://www.allenginsberg.org/index.php?page=nicanor-para-havana-1965|work=Allen Ginsberg Project|publisher=Allen Ginsberg Project|accessdate=June 21, 2012}}</ref> Parra is also the recipient of the prestigious [[Miguel de Cervantes Prize|Cervantes prize]] for Spanish-language literature.<ref>[http://www.thisischile.cl/8384/2/chile-the-land-of-poets/News.aspx Chile the land of poets]. This is Chile. January 3, 2013. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pablo Neruda]]\n* [[Vicente Huidobro]]\n* [[Violeta Parra]]\n* [[Nicanor Parra]]\n*[[Casa de Isla Negra]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chilean literature]]\n[[Category:Pablo Neruda]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Casa de neruda isla negra.jpg|thumb|[[Casa de Isla Negra|Pablo Neruda's house]], [[Isla Negra]], on the [[El Quisco]] [[Communes of Chile|commune]] coast. [[Pablo Neruda]] and his wife [[Matilde Urrutia]] are buried on these grounds. The site currently includes a museum in honour of the Chilean [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel laureate]].]]\n\nThe '''Coast of Poets''' is a cultural space in the [[Valpara\u00edso Region]] of [[Chile]], named for four world-renowned Chilean poets ([[Pablo Neruda]], [[Vicente Huidobro]], [[Nicanor Parra]] and [[Violeta Parra]]).\n\n==Description==\n\n[[File:Vicente huidobro.jpg|thumb|[[Vicente Huidobro]].]]\n\n[[File:Parra01f.PNG|thumb|[[Violeta Parra]].]]\n\n[[File:Perotti.jpg|thumb|[[Jos\u00e9 Perotti]].]]\n\nThe poets were the first to take up residence in this area, followed by various artists, thus creating a close link between the land and its creativity, projecting a symbolic imaginary that put Chile on the international cultural map. Places such as [[El Quisco]], [[Isla Negra]], [[Las Cruces (Chile)|Las Cruces]], [[El Tabo]] and [[Cartagena, Chile|Cartagena]] have become a hub for cultural activity.\n\nEl Quisco itself has been a meeting place for people such as [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel laureate]] [[Pablo Neruda]], who composed his famous poem ''Oda al Caldillo de Congr\u00edo'' (English: \u201cOde to Conger Chowder\u201d) in the local restaurant Chez Camilo;<ref name=\"Beach history\">[http://www.thisischile.cl/Article.aspx?id=2674&sec=196&itz=&eje=Turismo&idioma=2&t= Beaches with history on the central coast]. This is Chile. December 11, 2009. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref> folk singer [[Violeta Parra]]; writer, poet and composer [[Clara Solovera]]; cartoonist Ren\u00e9 R\u00edos Boettiger, otherwise known as [[Pepo (cartoonist)|Pepo]], the creator of famous character [[Condorito]];<ref name=\"Beach history\" /> artist [[Jos\u00e9 Perotti]]; and painter [[Camilo Mori]], who designed the official emblem for the municipality of El Quisco.\n\nIn [[Isla Negra]], two greats of the Chilean arts, Pablo Neruda and Violeta Parra, spent long periods of time. Chilean artist [[Violeta Parra]] gave classes in crafts and folklore in Isla Negra. She worked in [[ceramic]]s, [[oil painting]] and [[Hessian (cloth)|hessian cloth]].\n\nIsla Negra was given this name by [[Pablo Neruda]], upon him sighting the black rock in the sea near his house (Isla Negra means \"Black Island\" in English). When asked what the place would be called, he said \"Isla Negra, for those rocks.\u201d\n\n:\"The sea seemed cleaner to me than the land and this is why I came to live on the coast of my homeland, amid the great foam of Isla Negra.\"<ref>[http://radioantumapu.uchile.cl/programa-134-litoral-central-de-chile-cuna-de-poetas-e-identidad-nacional/ Programa 134: Litoral central de Chile, cuna de poetas e identidad nacional]. Radio Antumapu, University of Chile. January 7, 2012. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe [[Casa de Isla Negra]] is also to be found here,<ref>[http://www.fundacionneruda.org/es/isla-negra/direccion.html Isla Negra]. Fundaci\u00f3n Neruda. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref> now Neruda's place of burial, together with his wife Matilde. On one of his many returns to Chile, in 1937, the poet sought an ideal place to write his celebrated work [[Canto General]]. Neruda bought the site of Isla Negra from a Spanish former sailor who settled in the area following the sinking of his ship in [[Punta Arenas]]. With the help of architect Germ\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez Arias, he remodeled it to resemble a ship, with low ceilings and narrow passageways. The house would become a beloved refuge for the poet. It is now administered by the Neruda Foundation, with a museum exhibiting his extensive collection of objects, including ship figureheads, shells, bottles and maps.\n\nIn [[Cartagena, Chile|Cartagena]], poet [[Vicente Huidobro]] died in January 1948. Creator and exponent of [[Creacionismo|the creationist movement]], he is considered one of the \"four greats of Chilean poetry\", alongside [[Pablo Neruda]], [[Pablo de Rokha]] and [[Gabriela Mistral]]. A house-museum dedicated to the poet was opened here in September 2013.<ref>[http://www.gob.cl/english/featured/2013/04/06/president-pinera-inaugurates-vicente-huidobro-house-museum-in-cartagena.htm President Pi\u00f1era inaugurates Vicente Huidobro house museum in Cartagena] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822171323/http://www.gob.cl/english/featured/2013/04/06/president-pinera-inaugurates-vicente-huidobro-house-museum-in-cartagena.htm |date=August 22, 2016 }}. Presidency of Chile website (www.gob.cl). April 6, 2013. Retrieved April 26, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn [[Las Cruces (Chile)|Las Cruces]] lives [[Nicanor Parra]], a Chilean \"anti-poet\". Parra is credited for creating the \"anti-poetry\" movement, a literary expression that breaks with the traditional canons of poetic lyricism. One of his most recognised works is ''Poemas y Antipoemas'' (1954), where he replaces carefully written, metaphorical syntax with everyday, direct language. Considered one of the most influential Spanish poetry collections of the twentieth century, ''Poemas y Antipoemas'' is cited as an inspiration by American Beat writers like [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/story/2011/12/01/cervantes-prize-nicanor-parra.html | work=CBC News | title=Chilean poet Nicanor Parra wins Cervantes Prize | date=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nicanor Parra Havana 1965|url=http://www.allenginsberg.org/index.php?pa